<subSubSection id="C32E5B64894670D5868BC5BA7ED4D32C" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="065C6644BD929755B9EF07604F7DBFFC" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7EC4A718DABA7E9D788B572E10A8CDF9" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
Male has simple forceps, and is easily discriminated from that of other 
<taxonomicName id="101362296F0009035C242B0E542F657B" authorityName="Audinet-Serville" authorityYear="1831" class="Insecta" family="Diplatyidae" genus="Diplatys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Diplatys" order="Dermaptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="03E60861E5E7816FC46F88798555B1B5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Diplatys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species by the unique morphology of the virga: paired portion with developed flanges and a whip-like process at each tip. Flanged virgae have been reported in this genus only for 
<taxonomicName id="33DDB370943B4D569696083316BB9C45" genus="D." lsidName="D. jawalagiriensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="jawalagiriensis">
<emphasis id="90DD0D5A6BE8FDFC98C7DE7965763413" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">D. jawalagiriensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Kapoor, Bharadwaj &amp; Banerjee, 1971. However, almost no unpaired part is present at the base of each virga in 
<taxonomicName id="4690C9C1E4926C28D8995B10153E60AC" genus="D." lsidName="D. jawalagiriensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="jawalagiriensis">
<emphasis id="F2F1DD38540433F841418909E059C689" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">D. jawalagiriensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with no associated large sclerites in the penis lobe (vs short but conspicuous unpaired part and characteristic associated sclerites are present in 
<taxonomicName id="B7A65CD9D2CE087064DB2A1D2E1F52B3" genus="D." lsidName="D. sahyadriensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="sahyadriensis">
<emphasis id="E7AFCFC2B0A414FE2CA42C6E0907D1AD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">D. sahyadriensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov.).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CDF606E18D44699D2472689F79081C9F" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="description">
<paragraph id="FD9C4AF91C060697B728567CCDE3F9B2" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7A140D52B3C7E8DE304B75A6053F1BAE" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis id="6E8687DE17CADC9C458599FFDF0AE2CC" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Male</emphasis>
(holotype: Figs 
<figureCitation id="39511542B14F84C4E720FD09405F81A9" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Diplatys sahyadriensis sp. nov. (male holotype) a habitus b pronotum, tegmina and wings c thoracic sterna d left antenna e right foreleg f penultimate sternite and forceps g genitalia." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654592" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="777D934E03C7815EBC0C1EB1B03C932D" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Diplatys sahyadriensis sp. nov. (male holotype) a posterior half of penultimate sternite b left paramere c left penis (in repose), virga with whip-like distal processes (wdp), and associated sclerites (ds, disc-shaped sclerite; iss, inner serrated sclerite; mss, mid serrated sclerite; ods, outer denticulated sclerite)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654593" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">2</figureCitation>
). Measurements of body parts are shown in Table 
<tableCitation id="7BCE2D7F9DB614D0BF58D7BE3752D311" captionStart="Table 2" captionStartId="T2" captionText="Table 2. Measurements (mm) of the male holotype of Diplatys sahyadriensis sp. nov." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/107F9300E1473D0468C620E1E8F9D0CF" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" tableUuid="107F9300E1473D0468C620E1E8F9D0CF">2</tableCitation>
. Body generally dark brown. 2nd antennal segment and beyond light brown. Coxa, trochanter, basal third of femur, distal half of tibia, tarsi, base of tegmina, wings (excluding fustis), lateral and posterior margins of pronotum, and base of forceps whitish brown (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="056C6CEB3BD28FFAD8C4A083E70CBAE4" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Diplatys sahyadriensis sp. nov. (male holotype) a habitus b pronotum, tegmina and wings c thoracic sterna d left antenna e right foreleg f penultimate sternite and forceps g genitalia." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654592" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">1a-f</figureCitation>
). Abdomen and forceps densely pubescent (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="CF6CE74D3B2C430A23330EA4E7355FA7" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Diplatys sahyadriensis sp. nov. (male holotype) a habitus b pronotum, tegmina and wings c thoracic sterna d left antenna e right foreleg f penultimate sternite and forceps g genitalia." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654592" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">1a, f</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
