</paragraph>
<caption id="F96DC281F17E3AAB5447040C4A44B6A1" doi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654592" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" start="Figure 1" startId="F1">
<paragraph id="1D6CBBA500069E4A18AD766726D803E4" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis id="097EEA542045564D3373EB2994E04E06" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Figure 1.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="CEB88FB4526BC4B7ED299D5B7D041A72" authorityName="Karthik, Kamimura &amp; Kalleshwaraswamy" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Diplatyidae" genus="Diplatys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Diplatys sahyadriensis" order="Dermaptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sahyadriensis">
<emphasis id="D415E2B8850EE0C0AC096806660B7FF9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Diplatys sahyadriensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. (male holotype) 
<emphasis id="2384E9EE15FF3A0F8AD004742756352E" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">a</emphasis>
habitus 
<emphasis id="4CB5AC710B48B238F434C8CCBF25E7CD" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">b</emphasis>
pronotum, tegmina and wings 
<emphasis id="50937AC15FF109DB03769D8CE38308A2" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">c</emphasis>
thoracic sterna 
<emphasis id="ED6E83989EC5B12140D1A6E94828783A" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">d</emphasis>
left antenna 
<emphasis id="14BCCCD564B3C7AE68619C62C1776461" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">e</emphasis>
right foreleg 
<emphasis id="4E171E485209F5DBAFE3568ACA4DFA16" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">f</emphasis>
penultimate sternite and forceps 
<emphasis id="E0F1ADAEC53D8CED22804334AF45898E" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">g</emphasis>
genitalia.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="E4075857D7C93D04E74AA199967F5536" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
Head (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="76B6931EDCE705CA803448479672BEC1" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Diplatys sahyadriensis sp. nov. (male holotype) a habitus b pronotum, tegmina and wings c thoracic sterna d left antenna e right foreleg f penultimate sternite and forceps g genitalia." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654592" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">1a</figureCitation>
) slightly wider than long, widest in eye region; frons tumid but weakly depressed at apex; occiput strongly and widely depressed; transverse and median sutures visible but not conspicuous; posterior margin strongly emarginated in middle. Eyes prominent, distinctly longer than the post-ocular length. Antennae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F5BEDDB01135E52830AA5EEA315907BC" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Diplatys sahyadriensis sp. nov. (male holotype) a habitus b pronotum, tegmina and wings c thoracic sterna d left antenna e right foreleg f penultimate sternite and forceps g genitalia." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654592" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">1a, d</figureCitation>
) 17 segments or more (in holotype 15 left segments and 17 right segments remain), 1st expanded apically, slightly shorter than the combined length of 2nd to 4th; 2nd minute, shorter than width; 3rd long and slender; 4th slightly shorter than 3rd; 5th onwards segments gradually increasing in length and thinning up to 13th and 14th. Pronotum (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F22B724F418E2D71C424E641D632652F" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Diplatys sahyadriensis sp. nov. (male holotype) a habitus b pronotum, tegmina and wings c thoracic sterna d left antenna e right foreleg f penultimate sternite and forceps g genitalia." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654592" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">1b</figureCitation>
) longer than broad, narrowed posteriorly, anteriorly convex, sides almost straight, hind margin subrotundate, median sulcus distinct, prozona tumid and well differentiated from flat metazona. Tegmina (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="0E521F7EEE9A5AE1DE4620D67B7DB84B" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Diplatys sahyadriensis sp. nov. (male holotype) a habitus b pronotum, tegmina and wings c thoracic sterna d left antenna e right foreleg f penultimate sternite and forceps g genitalia." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654592" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">1b</figureCitation>
) well developed, humeral angles weak, costal margin straight, posterior margin obliquely convex, axillary angles weak, showing a broad triangular scutellum. Wings (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="AA2AB555D9EFB659D76CEF420314D82A" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Diplatys sahyadriensis sp. nov. (male holotype) a habitus b pronotum, tegmina and wings c thoracic sterna d left antenna e right foreleg f penultimate sternite and forceps g genitalia." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654592" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">1b</figureCitation>
) well developed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="75783461F8B611A3E9BCFB17D9DDFB1C" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
Prosternum (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="937AF8477F376FC51C171BC03129780E" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Diplatys sahyadriensis sp. nov. (male holotype) a habitus b pronotum, tegmina and wings c thoracic sterna d left antenna e right foreleg f penultimate sternite and forceps g genitalia." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654592" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">1c</figureCitation>
) elongate, with a constriction at the point of attachment of forelegs. Mesosternum (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F9246CA417C17A1EE987B8E642FACAFC" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Diplatys sahyadriensis sp. nov. (male holotype) a habitus b pronotum, tegmina and wings c thoracic sterna d left antenna e right foreleg f penultimate sternite and forceps g genitalia." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654592" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">1c</figureCitation>
) broader than prosternum, more or less rounded, deeply constricted at the point of attachment of the midlegs, truncated posteriorly. Metasternum (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="141276D25EC439551CF60E2E4D98818A" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Diplatys sahyadriensis sp. nov. (male holotype) a habitus b pronotum, tegmina and wings c thoracic sterna d left antenna e right foreleg f penultimate sternite and forceps g genitalia." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654592" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">1c</figureCitation>
) hexagonal, constricted at point of attachment of hindlegs, emarginate posteriorly.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="95B5A37E6D26A753BA601C6356127726" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
Abdomen (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="7374535D911955D117C2C45F4CAB9256" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Diplatys sahyadriensis sp. nov. (male holotype) a habitus b pronotum, tegmina and wings c thoracic sterna d left antenna e right foreleg f penultimate sternite and forceps g genitalia." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654592" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">1a</figureCitation>
) long, cylindrical, greatly enlarging from 7th tergite onwards. Penultimate sternite (Figs 
<figureCitation id="C9B8964B54F99340796E003DE147070E" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Diplatys sahyadriensis sp. nov. (male holotype) a habitus b pronotum, tegmina and wings c thoracic sterna d left antenna e right foreleg f penultimate sternite and forceps g genitalia." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654592" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">1f</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="551D20A89B0C2E029E9C6FB43151FC42" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Diplatys sahyadriensis sp. nov. (male holotype) a posterior half of penultimate sternite b left paramere c left penis (in repose), virga with whip-like distal processes (wdp), and associated sclerites (ds, disc-shaped sclerite; iss, inner serrated sclerite; mss, mid serrated sclerite; ods, outer denticulated sclerite)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654593" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">2a</figureCitation>
), relatively long, posterior margin weakly emarginated at middle. Ultimate tergite (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="A244CAD1E417343CAC4C749D7BBA54FE" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Diplatys sahyadriensis sp. nov. (male holotype) a habitus b pronotum, tegmina and wings c thoracic sterna d left antenna e right foreleg f penultimate sternite and forceps g genitalia." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654592" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">1a</figureCitation>
) transverse with two small, bifid, undulate depressions. Forceps (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="EA0356F0CE24D4C5CDDAED06330A47B6" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Diplatys sahyadriensis sp. nov. (male holotype) a habitus b pronotum, tegmina and wings c thoracic sterna d left antenna e right foreleg f penultimate sternite and forceps g genitalia." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654592" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">1a, f</figureCitation>
) about as long as the ultimate tergite, trigonal with ridge only present in basal two-thirds, branches tapering apically with pointed tip and without curving.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CCE2CD8C77FED3EEB3DD3056189460AB" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
Parameres (= external parameres; Figs 
<figureCitation id="C62D9D9BBD27DD2ED327555C87568689" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Diplatys sahyadriensis sp. nov. (male holotype) a habitus b pronotum, tegmina and wings c thoracic sterna d left antenna e right foreleg f penultimate sternite and forceps g genitalia." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654592" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">1g</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="3C0DD0F42D5C58EAE700EF5CB80D9A9D" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Diplatys sahyadriensis sp. nov. (male holotype) a posterior half of penultimate sternite b left paramere c left penis (in repose), virga with whip-like distal processes (wdp), and associated sclerites (ds, disc-shaped sclerite; iss, inner serrated sclerite; mss, mid serrated sclerite; ods, outer denticulated sclerite)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654593" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">2b</figureCitation>
) with an internal tooth at apical one-quarter and a small, deep concavity distal to it. Penis lobes (Figs 
<figureCitation id="875E126539E753DEC2FF6062938C5845" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Diplatys sahyadriensis sp. nov. (male holotype) a habitus b pronotum, tegmina and wings c thoracic sterna d left antenna e right foreleg f penultimate sternite and forceps g genitalia." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654592" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">1g</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="2B49F6D0524F73F4F20B977C9B5D2984" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Diplatys sahyadriensis sp. nov. (male holotype) a posterior half of penultimate sternite b left paramere c left penis (in repose), virga with whip-like distal processes (wdp), and associated sclerites (ds, disc-shaped sclerite; iss, inner serrated sclerite; mss, mid serrated sclerite; ods, outer denticulated sclerite)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654593" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">2c</figureCitation>
) slightly shorter than the parameres, each with a denticulated sclerite (= outer denticulated sclerite; ods), two differently shaped, serrated sclerites (mid serrated sclerite [mss] and inner serrated sclerite [iss]), a disc-shaped sclerite (ds), and a bifurcated virga. Virga (Figs 
<figureCitation id="B9D0F7109135EC75F97391A18C2CC0CC" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Diplatys sahyadriensis sp. nov. (male holotype) a habitus b pronotum, tegmina and wings c thoracic sterna d left antenna e right foreleg f penultimate sternite and forceps g genitalia." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654592" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">1g</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="8FC9CC882957E1EA58223C58A0A56A72" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Diplatys sahyadriensis sp. nov. (male holotype) a posterior half of penultimate sternite b left paramere c left penis (in repose), virga with whip-like distal processes (wdp), and associated sclerites (ds, disc-shaped sclerite; iss, inner serrated sclerite; mss, mid serrated sclerite; ods, outer denticulated sclerite)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654593" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">2c</figureCitation>
) with very short, unpaired part, and long paired part. Each branch of paired part convoluted, slender, but with well-developed flange, and tips widened with a whip-like distal process (wdp).
</paragraph>
<caption id="42A8C37D92003346335F5BA6ABD02CF2" doi="10.3897/zookeys.1088.79416.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/654593" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" start="Figure 2" startId="F2">
<paragraph id="A8086E9CFA17B4288351697DC69E3261" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis id="02BA32FF6D22DA814C8D12FE426E6C12" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Figure 2.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="8DC46C62591A613C110D474E2EF60D90" authorityName="Karthik, Kamimura &amp; Kalleshwaraswamy" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Diplatyidae" genus="Diplatys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Diplatys sahyadriensis" order="Dermaptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sahyadriensis">
<emphasis id="71BEAE666C3FCA5390D1EAB741616C09" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Diplatys sahyadriensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. (male holotype) 
<emphasis id="DE7A2CCF4E6AA74558079563A75A2DA7" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">a</emphasis>
posterior half of penultimate sternite 
<emphasis id="7D9383E2D592EB07A827D14777C11E68" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">b</emphasis>
left paramere 
<emphasis id="B6D76ED4305F4B5F602491047479A908" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">c</emphasis>
left penis (in repose), virga with whip-like distal processes (wdp), and associated sclerites (ds, disc-shaped sclerite; iss, inner serrated sclerite; mss, mid serrated sclerite; ods, outer denticulated sclerite).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="69C733B8E886F3679DDB8478C717A20A" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis id="60872FA4E99CFC6B71EEA05928C0FEEF" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Female.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="62AEA517BEE5A88956E1CCEE2FCC636A" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="016E2686732378DDF901CBC7F05133DF" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2E590ED4672BB534F9FCEF428722E13A" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
The specific epithet 
<taxonomicName id="767D593DDEC9E398EB69746B41AF8AE8" authorityName="Karthik, Kamimura &amp; Kalleshwaraswamy" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Diplatyidae" genus="Diplatys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Diplatys sahyadriensis" order="Dermaptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sahyadriensis">
<emphasis id="DB2E3D8F834BF97E1C3D06FBE9D1C485" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Diplatys sahyadriensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
refers to the type locality: the specimen was collected from the Sahyadri Ranges, which is a gateway to the Western Ghats of Karnataka.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3A2A6A3CE3EC20C6BF90BB651EB744AD" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="6D948547AFCA0DA4B66FAE18C8F571E8" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="24FA9C5772CFE4E086F0211EA33158D7" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Only known from Shivamogga, Karnataka, India.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1158541CF2E94421724A0F3F165D679C" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="bioecology">
<paragraph id="866545891B3C569B55C116BB8A7D6CF0" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Bioecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A9AA4D4CA0DB7D73A2C37519C44ABC02" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
The male specimen (holotype) was collected from whorls of sugarcane 
<taxonomicName id="C6F4559328064E83253B8F1C9CAB003A" class="Liliopsida" family="Gramineae" genus="Saccharum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Saccharum officinarum" order="Poales" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="officinarum">
<emphasis id="342F443D91834838DC8EFC516544FBB1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Saccharum officinarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. (
<taxonomicName id="FB1E95A1544AE95707FE336514DDB42A" family="Gramineae" genus="Saccharum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="phylum">Angiospermae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="DB7F569E4605A5B8718742E0818CA107" class="Liliopsida" family="Gramineae" genus="Saccharum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="family">Gramineae</taxonomicName>
). The collection site is in a mixed area of sugarcane and paddy fields. Faecal pellets were seen on the leaves of sugarcane, suggesting that specimen had been in that place for some time, possibly taking advantage of this shaded spot.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
